y = 2 + \int^x_2 [t - ty(t) \,\, dt]
\implies \frac{dy}{dt} = \frac{dy}{dt}\cdot 2 + \frac{dy}{dt} \int^x_2 [t - t\cdot y(t) \,\, dt]
y(2)=2
\frac {d}{dx}\Big(\int^x_2 [t - ty(t)] \,\, dt\Big)=x-x y(x)
y(x) = 2 + \int^x_2 [t - ty(t)] \,\, dt
y'(x)=x -xy(x)
y(x)=1+e^{2-\frac{x^2}{2}}
